THOUGHT: I will modify the copysign nesting combine to check fast-math flags to avoid propagating a potentially NaN operand into an outer nnan copysign, then submit the patch.

```bash
sed -i '2673,2677c\
    // Propagate sign argument through nested calls with care:\
    // copysign Mag, (copysign ?, X) --> copysign Mag, X\
    // This is only safe if we are not introducing a possibly-NaN operand to an\
    // outer copysign that has the no-nans fast-math flag. The inner copysign\
    // (copysign ?, X) produces a non-NaN result regardless of X (its magnitude\
    // comes from its first argument). Replacing it with X directly when the\
    // outer call has nnan but the inner does not could expose a NaN operand to\
    // the outer intrinsic and violate the nnan assumption, leading to poison in\
    // verification.\
    if (auto *InnerCI = dyn_cast<IntrinsicInst>(Sign))\
      if (InnerCI->getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::copysign) {\
        Value *InnerSign = InnerCI->getArgOperand(1);\
        if (!(II->hasNoNaNs() && !InnerCI->hasNoNaNs()))\
          return replaceOperand(*II, 1, InnerSign);\
      }' llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineCalls.cpp && submit-patch
```

